<dl id="n19070a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n19" href="#n19070a">N19 (VI.B.19)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n19all.htm#n19070a"> 70(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>avice<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> / father / surrogate <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n19070a"><li>FW 480.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n19070a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n19070a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n19070a">MS BL 47484a-40</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:175 <a name="rAd4" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rAd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd4.htm#n19070a">Draft: III&sect;3A.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The wolf man&apos;s]</font> fear of his father was the strongest motive for his falling ill, and his ambivalent attitude towards every <mark>father-surrogate</mark> was the doiminating feature of his life as well as of his behaviour during the treatment. If in my patient&apos;s case the wolf was merely a first father-surrogate, the question arises whether the hidden content in the fairy tales of the wolf that ate up the little goats and of &lsquo;Little Red Riding-Hood&rsquo; may not simply be infantile fear of the father. Moreover. my patient&apos;s father had the characteristic shown by so many people in relation to their children, of indulging in &ldquo;<i>affectionate abuse</i>&rdquo;; and it is possible that during the patient&apos;s earlier years his father &hellip; may more than once, as he caressed the little boy or played with him, have threatened in fun to &lsquo;gobble him up&rsquo; <small> Sigmund Freud, <a name="SFWM2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SFWM2"><cite title="source">&ldquo;From the History of an Infantile Neurosis (The &lsquo;Wolf Man&rsquo;)&rdquo;</cite></a> (1925) 502</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
